<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DEPARTMENT OF ENERGY AND CLIMATE CHANGE</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Department of Energy and Climate Change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> (HOT51)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Government welcomes the opportunity to input into the Committee’s inquiry into heat. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the last two years, the Government has made significant progress in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">meeting the challenge of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">chang</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing how</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> we produce and consume heat.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In March 2012, we published a “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Strategic Framework</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">”</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for Heat. The document set out for the first time a framework for solving the problem of ensuring affordable, secure and low carbon heating.  It also set out the Government’s vision for heat in the decades ahead: a future with secure supplies of low carbo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n and renewable energy at affordable prices, supporting a strong UK economy.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The 2012 document began an important public dialogue. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In March this year, the Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> followed this up with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Future of Heating: Meeting the Challenge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> proposes po</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">licies to deliver the Government’s visions across four key areas:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">industrial heat and combined heat and power;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">heat delivered through heat networks;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">heating and cooling in buildings; and </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the implications for our energy grids and infrastructure.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A program</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">me of w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ork</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, led by DECC and involving other Government departments and Local Authorities, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is currently underway to deliver these commitments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, working closely with the private sector and with academia, among others</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This memorandum will address each of th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e questions raised by the committee in turn.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:none">Q1 and 2 – Reducing demand for heat</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:none">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Government’s approach to reducing energy demand for heat is part of its overall approach to reducing carbon emissions, as set out in the Carbon Plan.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nergy efficiency </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is one of the most cost-effective means of cutting carbon and it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> featured in all of the Carbon Plan scenarios.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ide-scale take-up of energy efficiency measures the UK can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">stimulate growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> save consumers money. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Over [80%] of energy consumed in b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uildings is used as heat, so m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">anaging our demand for heat has a key role to play in this.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are a number of policy instruments that have been put in place to manage heat demand.  By 31 December 2012, the Carbon Emissions Reduction Target (CERT) had de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">livered around 6 million professionally installed insulation measures by placing an obligation on the 6 largest energy suppliers to save CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Community Energy Saving Programme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CESP) was a pilot programme designed to deliver energy efficiency </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">retrofits to low income households, street by street.  By 31 December 2012, it had delivered 16.31 million lifetime tonnes of CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">savings, through almost 500 schemes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">. . </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Energy Company Obligation (ECO) replaced CERT, CESP and Warm Front from 1 Janu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ary 2013.   It forms part of the Government’s programme to tackle fuel poverty and works alongside the Green Deal to provide more support for energy efficiency measures, including insulation for harder to treat properties.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Green Deal is a market-based</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> scheme which offers households and businesses a new finance mechanism to cover energy-saving improvements without having to pay all the costs up front.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> It </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> help</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> drive take-up of measures such as insulation and more efficient heating technologies.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In November 2012, the Government published its Energy Efficiency Strategy.  As part of this, DECC is commissioning research into the potential of advanced heating controls to reduce domestic energy demand and developing a trial to study the impact of adv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ice on how to use heating controls provided when boiler checks are carried out. Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e trial will report results in s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ummer 2014.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q3.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What should be done to ensure methods of calculating biomass GHG balance represent an accurate picture? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Greenhouse Gas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(GHG) lifecycle methodology for solid biomass and biogas used by the RHI is as set out under the 2009 EU Renewable Energy Directive</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This EU approach considers the direct emissions impact of the biomass feedstock, from cultivation, harvesting, processing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and transport. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">13.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The methodology used for the RHI does not include possible indirect impacts, such as indirect land use change. However, we consider it essential the UK uses the EU approach to provide consistency, to support a single European market, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to avoid unnecessary burdens, particularly on smaller biomass producers and users. Moreover, the expectation is that most solid biomass or biogas used for heat in the UK will be from lower value residues or process waste: and, that where it is a dedicated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">perennial energy crop, most will be grown on low quality or degraded land unsuitable for food production. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">14.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DECC is currently developing a bioenergy calculator - the BEaC (Biomass Emissions and Counterfactual) Model, which will be in a format similar to DE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CC’s existing 2050 pathways calculator. This model considers all potential GHG emissions, including indirect impacts and carbon stock changes in forests which are not accounted for by the 2009 EU Renewable Energy Directive. Users can choose various scenari</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">os for bioenergy and the calculator then models lifecycle GHG emissions resulting from those scenarios.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This tool will inform the UK’s future negotiations on global accounting and future energy and decarbonisation targets internationally. It will also be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">used to inform </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">long-term </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bioenergy policies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:none">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:none">Q4.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:none">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:none">There are sustainability guidelines for biomass, do these go far enough?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">15.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The use of biomass for heat  was identified by the UK Bioenergy Strategy</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as a low risk priority pathway that the UK would want to encourage. The high conversion efficiencies of heat generation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mean biomass heat is an attractive, cost-effective technology that c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> make a significant contribution to the UK meeting its 2020 renew</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ables target. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The longer term role of biomass for heating is less straightforward (given the competing other users for which a finite bio-energy resource is likely to be needed), but modelling implies it could have a significant role, especially where high</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> temperature heat is required, as in industrial processes. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">16.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We want the UK to be at the forefront in the EU in ensuring biomass supplies are sustainable and are bringing in robust RHI sustainability standards.  These are set out in the Government Response to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">‘Providing Certainty, improving performance’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> consultation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> published in February</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and include a GHG lifecycle emissions target to ensure genuine emissions savings and land criteria to prevent deforestation or environmental degradation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">17.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The GHG lifecycle emissions target will be a minimum 60% GHG lifecycle saving</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s compared to the GHG emissions of the EU fossil heat average; this is significantly tougher than the 35% initial saving recommended by the European Commission in their 2010 report</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. To be eligible for support, RHI installations will be required to demonst</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rate meeting the GHG target from April 2014; and the land criteria from April 2015.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">18.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Government intends to review the effectiveness of the UK’s approach as part of the UK Bioenergy Strategy Review in 2017. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q5.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What will the local environmental impa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ct be from the use of heat generation in urban areas, for example CHP units?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">19.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Studies suggest that biomass boilers and CHP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, both biomass and natural gas fired,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in urban areas could, in the absence of mitigating measures, have an adverse impact on; air qual</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ity (particulate matter (PM) and oxides of nitrogen (NO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">x))</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and noise. The RHI is introducing emissions limits and targeted tariff values for biomass CHP and other biomass boilers which seek to mitigate their impact on air quality.  Air quality impacts will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> be kept under review. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">20.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The air pollutant emissions of biomass boilers and CHP plant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(of all fuel types) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">above 20MW thermal input are controlled by Environmental Permitting requirements.  Smaller plants are governed by the Clean Air Act 1993 and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">plann</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing process.  Defra has assisted with the development of guidance for local authorities on addressing air pollution impacts of CHP and biomass boilers. By careful plant location and good acoustic design, the noise impact of CHP can be mitigated. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:none">Q6.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:none">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:none">What</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:none"> are the relative merits of using gas to directly provide space heating compared to centralised electricity production plus domestic heat pumps?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:none">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:none"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:uppercase">21.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Different approaches to heating bring different benefits.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eat demand shows more variability than electricity demand across the day and across the seasons. UK electricity demand </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">varies between 20 and 55</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">GW</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> daily</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  Heat demand across all sectors can vary between 150 and 400GW during the coldest winter days. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:uppercase">22.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The ga</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s network helps manage variability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with suppliers able to purchase gas quickly from a number of sources. The gas grid is able to handle short term spikes in demand due to the gas market’s liquidity. The electricity grid is less able to accommodate spikes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in demand without substantial spare generation capacity to meet peak winter demand.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:uppercase">23.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The high-level conclusions of the economic modelling commissioned for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Meeting the challenge </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">document suggest there could still be a limited role for natural gas in 205</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">0 to meet peaks in heat demand on the coldest days of the year. It suggests this could be more cost-effective than the alternative of full electrification. We are also seeing the development of hybrid heating systems that use gas and renewable energy sourc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es, which could play a part in meeting peak heat demand.  Energy efficient measures, smart meters, smarter electricity grids and developments in electricity and thermal storage will also help</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, as will the development of low carbon heat networks with multip</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">le heat sources</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:uppercase">24.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">When considering the relative merits of gas heating against electric heat pumps, costs of both fuel and infrastructure both now and in the future have to be considered.  For gas, there is the issue of the cost of maintaining the gas netw</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ork; for electricity, there are the issues of the cost of reinforcement of the local electricity distribution grids. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In both cases, some built-in redundancy is likely to be needed to ensure peak demand can be met.  This is why energy storage and demand-sid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e response is so important. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q7.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Why is community heating/CHP not more common in the UK? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">25.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The amount of heat supplied to buildings in the UK via heat networks is around 2% of domestic, public sector and commercial heat demand. This amounts to around 2000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> networks serving approximately 210,000 dwellings and 1700 commercial and public buildings across the UK.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">26.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many of the schemes in operation today in the UK originate from the 1960s and 70s. For a number of reasons, including the waning popularity of high-r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ise housing developments, and the poor design, construction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, maintenance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and economic performance of some early schemes, heat networks fell out of favour. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">European countries where they remained popular have tended to have less well-developed natural gas gr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ids than the UK. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Over the past decade, as local authorities have looked for ways to cut carbon emissions and address fuel poverty, the case for heat networks has strengthened. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Consumer reaction to networked heat is not straightforward; it can range from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">very positive where bills come down and reliability goes up (in comparison, for example, with electric heaters in a flat), all the way through to negative where a flat rate is charged, which is deemed to high and bearing no relation to actual heat consumed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The majority of heat consumers, however, are far more familiar with boilers and remain ignorant of the district heating option.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">27.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Government and other analysis over the previous years, including new modelling presented as an Annex to our March heat docum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ent, and responses from a wide variety of stakeholders, have shown that modern, low carbon heat networks can have a crucial role to play in a sustainable heating future, especially where heat demand is highly concentrated and a range of types of heat suppl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y might be available, ie in urban areas. Major cities across the UK are already pursuing this route, but they often encounter barriers to development.. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">28.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To help local authorities and local economic partnerships to overcome the financial, commercial and te</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">chnical skills barriers to developing low carbon heat networks,  DECC is establishing a new Heat Networks Delivery Unit to help local authorities and local economic partnerships to overcome the financial, commercial and technical skills barriers to develop</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing low carbon heat networks.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This will be up and running by October this year[</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">footnote</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">once cleared, attach link to announcement of HNDU investment director appointment].</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">29.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Over and above networked heat projects, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Government is keen to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">see more local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> communities getting involved in reducing energy use, managing energy demand and collectively purchasing energy to get a better deal.   We will be publishing a Community Energy Strategy in the autumn, which will identify the potential of community energy p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rojects in the UK to bring benefits to communities while helping to tackle climate change and maintain energy security. It will consider how to help community energy projects overcome the main barriers they face.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">30.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK CHP capacity has grown year on year to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.1 GW</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  in 2012 contributing 6.4% of electricity generated. Most of this capacity (89%) is industrial supplying industrial process heat. The rate of growth has been slow, due to CHP projects facing significantly higher hurdle rates than power-only generat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ion projects and difficulties for small CHP operators in securing a good price for the electricity they produce. DECC is working on a bespoke policy to support deployment of additional CHP capacity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, provided this can be shown to be lower carbon that the el</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ectricity it is displacing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q8.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What are the lock-in, costs and GHG savings from the promotion of different forms of domestic heating solution?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">31.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Committee has helpfully set out that it would like information on: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the benefit of space saving through s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">witching to a combi-boiler discouraging the switch back to a hot water tank </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">if </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the UK energy system goes down an electrification route; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">capital intensive solutions such as biomass-based district heating systems locking people into a system that could </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">become less economically or environmentally beneficial if competition for biomass from energy/non-energy sources increases; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">some domestic fuel combustion heating systems potentially facing problems in the future if</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">air quality standards are substantial</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ly tightened.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">32.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The share of the market for combi boilers is now approaching two-thirds of all boilers in the UK. The issue of the need for hot water tanks in the future was highlighted in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Meeting the Challenge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">33.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Industry reports</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> suggest that of those hou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">seholders that do not currently own a hot water tank, the proportion saying that they would find it easy to find space, and those saying it would be difficult, are of the same order. Technology may help that proportion of people who find the space requirem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ent for a new heat store difficult to meet.  First, hybrid heat pumps that incorporate condensing boilers will allow for the supply of hot water, thus negating much of the need for a thermal store. Secondly, developments in thermal storage, currently being</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> researched by DECC, may make kit smaller and more efficient.  Thirdly, heat networks can offer storage capacity at scale, an important consideration in terms of matching supply with demand which in turn has wider benefits.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Heat networks also enable easy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">transition between fossil fuel and low/zero carbon sources of heat. It allows changing on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> large heat supply </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(or switching between a small number of different centralised heat sources) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rather than changing many individual boilers.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">34.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As stated above, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK encourages the use of biomass heat in buildings and for industrial processes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">So, it is important that investors are given sufficient certainty to bring forward large scale investments without being subject to the risk that changing environmental and s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ustainability criteria will create stranded assets. Therefore we have decided that for existing non-domestic biomass RHI installations the sustainability criteria will be “grandfathered” from the date the criteria are first introduced under the RHI.  For n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ew biomass heat installations, including domestic installations, grandfathering of the criteria will be applied at the point of accreditation. In the longer-term, biomass sustainability controls could be changed, so new installations accredited after these</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> changes may have to meet different standards.  We believe this offers a sensible balance between providing the certainty needed to bring forward new biomass heat generation while still allowing us the flexibility to adjust the controls for new installatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ns</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">35.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">New installations of biomass systems will also need to meet air quality standards in relation to PM and NO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">x</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Domestic legacy installations, installed between 15</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> July 2009 and the launch of the scheme, will not need to meet this requirement. The air</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> quality standards will also apply to all biomass systems which join the non-domestic RHI from September 24</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 2013. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q9.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Should the government take any further specific actions in relation to cooling?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">36.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cooling in the UK is primarily geared towards </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">removing excessive heat gain in non-domestic buildings such as offices, to maintain comfortable ambient temperatures. Whilst mechanical cooling in buildings is currently responsible for 4% of the total energy demand, cooling in homes is less significant; a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ccounting for 1% of household energy use</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Commissioned reports into the possible effects of climate change suggest that the domestic uptake of air conditioning</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is likely to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> rise. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">37.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Meeting the Challenge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> proposed a number of areas that we need to examine i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n tackling cooling in non-domestic buildings, such as improving our understanding of the way non-domestic buildings work and the way they are used to in relation to heating, ventilation and air conditioning systems. This is a complex area as the non-domest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ic building stock is diverse and the buildings are used so differently. Currently cooling is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">predominantly carried out through</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> electric air conditioning although there are other measures that can be used as part of a new build or retrofit development. Our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">March document, for example, pointed to the increased role for renewable systems, such as reversible heat pumps in heating and cooling buildings. There may also be scope to combine summer-time cooling with solar photovoltaic electricity generation. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with industry and  wider stakeholder groups on these issues to decide on the specific actions that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">may be needed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q10.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Why does the RHI not seem to promote heat pumps successfully</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">38.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The non-domestic RHI currently only incorporates ground source</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> heat pumps (GSHPs).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> There is an existing strong and growing market for reversible air to air heat pumps (AAHPs) therefore we do not propose introducing RHI support for this technology. Towards the end of 2012, consultations closed which discussed the pos</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sibility of introducing support for heating-only AAHPs and air to water heat pumps. We are currently reviewing the responses and other evidence and plan to publish our decision as to whether or not RHI support is appropriate in autumn 2013.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">39.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In response to industry and market feedback, DECC has looked at the evidence on cost data and heat usage assumptions used to set the levels of tariffs when the non-domestic scheme was launched alongside the level of uptake so far under the scheme and evide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nce from the renewable heat industry and market. As a result of this, we launched </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/non-domestic-rhi-early-tariff-review"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:none">the Non-Domestic Scheme Early Tariff Review consultation</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in June which set ou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t how the Government proposed to respond to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the low up take of some technologies, including GSHPs, in the scheme so far, to ensure that renewable heat can make an effective contribution to our 2020 renewable energy targets, support the UK renewable heat in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dustry and achieve decarbonisation of our heat supply by 2050. The consultation has now closed and we plan to announce the outcomes this autumn.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">40.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Another factor affecting the deployment of GSHPs is the construction industry.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> GSHPs are most commonly instal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">led as part of new-build construction projects, as retro-fitting is often not an option in older properties due to a lack of space for a suitably sized ground-loop.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> As the number of new-build construction projects have declined over the past few years, so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has the demand for GSHP installations.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">41.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The domestic scheme, which will open for applications in spring 2014, will support ground and air source heat pumps.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q11.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How successful will the RHI be when rolled out to households?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">42.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are confident that the dom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">estic RHI will successfully incentivise the uptake of renewable heat technologies, and anticipate 3.9TWh of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">domestic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">renewable heat will be supported through RHI by 2020/21. We estimate that this equates to cumulatively 745,000 installations by 2020/21. We</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> expect to see steady growth in installations over the next few years, preparing the ground for mass rollout of renewable heating to households in the 2020s and 2030s. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">43.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The final policy was designed through extensive engagement over the consultation period, including consumer experience to date and consumer behaviour research by Ipsos MORI.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">44.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are undertaking a range of activities to encourage uptake ahead of the schem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e’s launch next year.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The DECC-led RHI Consumer Protection and Empowerment and RHI Industry Advisory Groups are developing consumer engagement and industry promotional tools. Finally, DECC and Ofgem are working to streamline the application process.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Thermal storage is a potential useful method of balancing electricity/energy demand both diurnally and annually.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> What is government policy doing to promote thermal storage, and should it do more/different? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">45.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Low Carbon Innovation Coordination Group</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s Technology Innovation Needs Assessment for Heat, September 2012, identified heat storage as a priority area for support in the near future and research programmes are already in place.  A low carbon innovation strategy, to co-ordinate and guide potentia</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l future public sector funding in this area, will be published before the end of 2013.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As stated above, heat networks store heat and connect to large thermal stores.   DECC is providing £6m to be managed by the Heat Networks Delivery Unit, which will supp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ort local authorities and local economic partnerships to develop heat networks.  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">46.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition, the Energy Technology Institute is running a £100m multi-year project looking at smart systems and heat, which includes demand-side response and storage options</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The programme objectives are </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Understanding real mass-market consumer behaviour, requirements and profiles in order to design and communicate effective service products</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The provision of energy services and integrated products (i.e. the physical elements) to consumers in domestic and commercial buildings (primarily domestic &amp; retrofit) </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Key focus on space and water heating (comfort, cleanliness), but including other energ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y service needs in or connected to buildings (e.g. vehicle charging) </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Understanding the evolution of the whole energy system out to 2050, including buildings retrofits and energy distribution system choices - See more at: http://www.eti.co.uk/technology_pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ogrammes/smart_systems_and_heat#sthash.5QXdpt69.dpuf</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">“The future of heating: a strategic framework for low carbon heat”. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DECC, March 2012</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span><a href="http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=Oj:L:2009:140:0016:0062:en:PDF"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=Oj:L:2009:140:0016:0062:en:PDF</span></a><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DECC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> (2012) UK Bioenergy Strategy </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/48337/5142-bioenergy-strategy-.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/48337/5142-bioenergy-strategy-.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a hr